commit.message:
Formatting in doc of `@=?` and `@?=`: put some emphasis

Should help readability.
Allow ansi-terminal-1.1

CI: include GHC 9.8, bump actions, separate cache restore/save

Also:
- remove superfluous `cabal update` and `cabal freeze`
- always save cache (even if build or test failed)
- use precise GHC version in cache key
- address shellcheck warnings
Mention the proper env vars for usage in MinGW

Improve ‘filterByPattern’ to not keep empty subtrees

This way console reporter will not need to print group headings when
group contains no tests, amoung other things.
Simplify further: \r is sufficient to clear whole line, no need for additional escape sequence

Use simpler ‘\r’ instead of cursor manipulation escape sequences

This primarily benefits displaying progress in Emacs’s shell-mode
since it supports \r but doesn’t support ansi escapes other than
color manipulation ones.
Fixed issue #395
Avoid blanket import from `GHC.Conc`
WASI CI: fix/update splitmix commit
Allow containers-0.7

launchTestTree: use IntMap strict in values

At the moment we use `Data.IntMap` which is lazy in values,
and we initialise values with thunks `testStatus <$> testActions`.
This is outright silly: `testStatus` is just a selector for `TVar`
field, forcing it to WHNF can do no harm.

We also take an opportunity to replace `IntMap.fromList` with
`IntMap.fromDistinctAscList`.

statusMapResult: use IntSet instead of IntMap ()

It seems the only reason behind `IntMap ()` was the absense of
`Data.IntMap.withoutKeys`, which was only added in `containers-0.5.8`.

Make computeAlignment more efficient

Currently `Test.Tasty.Ingredients.ConsoleReporter.computeAlignment` evaluation
is extremely inefficient: firstly because `data Maximum` lacks strictness
annotations, and secondly because `foldTestTree` operates not even
over `Maximum a`, but over `Int -> Maximum a`.

The patch improves efficiency of `computeAlignment` and arguably makes
its implementation simpler.

Teach the HUnit Steps provider to log progress

A cheap improvement to also show the steps as the tests are running.
tasty-quickcheck now requires tasty >= 1.5
Change source-repository location from git:// to https:// (#385)
Make cabal check happy: add upper bounds and increase descriptions
Bump tasty-hunit version to 0.10.1
Finalize changelogs for tasty-1.5

Allow --pattern|-p option to repeat

The effect of multiple -p options is the same as &&-ing the expressions
together, but allowing them to be specified in separate options makes
scripting test commands simpler.

CI: bump ghc-wasm-meta for stable bindists

Follow-up to https://github.com/UnkindPartition/tasty/pull/372 as mentioned
there. The pinned bindists are now stable and won't expire.
Final polishing

Fix CI: turn off haddock step for GHC 8.4

This haddock is too old for parsing constructor field documentation.
Fix haddocks for Test.Tasty.Ingredients.ConsoleReporter.TestOutput

Updated tasty-quickcheck CHANGELOG.md file

And bumped version to 0.10.3.
Modify progress percent to cover the previous progress.
Fixed performance regression when using --no-progress
Improve the performance by avoiding spinning in ppProgressOrResult

Avoid potential multi-line progress lines

Without these changes, I get multiple dots from QuickCheck on the terminal with

  --quickcheck-tests=1000000

Either of them suffices for a fix, but they both make sense.
